 DESIGN FLAWS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. Totem assignment encoding is a hack
   _totemAssignment[] in GameSetupMenu encodes two conceptually different
   things in one byte: values < GenericTotemRoles::COUNT (3) = generic
   role, values ≥ 3 = totemVar index offset by 3. This is fragile —
   adding a new generic role breaks all existing totemVar indices silently.
   Should be a struct: { bool isNamed; uint8_t value; }.

2. Enlight via global pointer
   Games declare extern Enlight* enlightPtr (e.g. GameFreeForAll.cpp ~47).
   The pointer is initialized in the sketch, but nothing prevents a game
   from dereferencing it before initialization, and there's zero
   compile-time safety. Enlight should be injected into GameRunner::begin()
   or into the game callbacks as a parameter.

3. Player ID space vs team map mismatch
   _teamMap in GameRunner is size 16 (PlayerDefs::MAX_PLAYER_ID).
   RadioPacket.senderId is a uint8_t (0–255). Players with IDs ≥ 16 are
   silently placed on team 0. This isn't enforced at the radio layer, and
   PlayerDefs::playerNames only has meaningful entries for IDs 0–9 anyway
   ("Unknown" for 10–15). The implicit maximum of ~9 real players is never
   stated or checked.

4. Player ID 0 ("00-None") is ambiguous
   ID 0 is used as "None"/unassigned in TotemVar::id (default = 0), but
   is technically a valid RadioPacket.senderId. If a device accidentally
   transmits with ID 0, it could corrupt score slots. Should be an
   explicit sentinel (0xFF or similar) for "unassigned totem."

5. Message type collisions with no registry
   Game-specific message types (e.g. MSG_LIT = 0x10) are locally defined
   per game file. Nothing stops two games from using the same value.
   typeId filtering prevents cross-game collisions at runtime, but this
   will cause confusion when debugging and could break if two game sessions
   run with adjacent typeIds.

6. Config blob truncation is silent
   game_apply_config() has no total-length check. A truncated blob
   (e.g. partial radio delivery) passes the typeId check and is
   deserialized by fixed offset arithmetic, silently producing garbage
   configVar / totemVar values. The function returns false only on
   typeId mismatch or buffer shorter than 2 bytes.

7. Discovery window is too rigid
   ROSTER_WINDOW_MS (3 s) is hardcoded. The DM can't extend it if they
   know a player is still booting. Players also don't re-broadcast during
   the window — they rely on their one MSG_ROSTER timing. A player booting
   at second 2.9 is missed.


